00:50:14,968 --> 00:50:17,971
You'll find bedding
in the closet on the shelf.

779
00:50:19,014 --> 00:50:23,018
In the morning, the area will be
returned to sitting-room mode

780
00:50:23,101 --> 00:50:25,437
no later than 0700 hours.

781
00:50:29,524 --> 00:50:30,901
What was that?

782
00:50:33,570 --> 00:50:34,779
Nothing.

783
00:50:35,864 --> 00:50:38,867
Next time snap it out!

784
00:50:41,119 --> 00:50:45,415
Thumb to palm, index finger
through little digit, smartly aligned,

785
00:50:46,750 --> 00:50:49,336
sharp to the hairline, down!

786
00:50:53,965 --> 00:50:58,345
Too many men, far better than you,
have executed that courtesy.

787
00:50:59,012 --> 00:51:02,140
And if you're smart,
you won't try it again.

788
00:51:06,269 --> 00:51:10,649
This bat has got sharper radar
than the Nautilus.

789
00:51:11,149 --> 00:51:13,610
Don't fuck with me, Charlie.

790
00:51:24,704 --> 00:51:27,207
See you get a good night's sleep, son.

791
00:51:39,386 --> 00:51:42,013
<i>It's a lovely day today</i>

792
00:51:42,097 --> 00:51:44,933
<i>So, whatever you gotta do</i>

793
00:51:45,016 --> 00:51:48,269
<i>You got a lovely day to do it in,
that's true</i>

794
00:51:54,776 --> 00:51:56,778
Good morning, Charlie.

795
00:51:59,072 --> 00:52:00,824
Good morning.

796
00:52:01,157 --> 00:52:02,909
This is Sofia, Charlie.

797
00:52:03,034 --> 00:52:05,287
She's a magician with a needle.

798
00:52:05,370 --> 00:52:08,373
Sofia's workin' me up
a little Glen Plaid number,

799
00:52:08,498 --> 00:52:11,668
and I've asked her if she'd put
something together for you.

800
00:52:11,751 --> 00:52:13,962
I don't need any clothes, Colonel.

801
00:52:14,045 --> 00:52:17,132
Standard issue for an upscale
urban assignment.

802
00:52:17,424 --> 00:52:20,010
You don't like the clothes, Charlie,
on completion of duty,

803
00:52:20,093 --> 00:52:22,137
you can give 'em away.

804
00:52:22,429 --> 00:52:25,807
Juice, coffee, and other assorted goodies
on the trolley over there.

805
00:52:25,890 --> 00:52:28,101
Get yourself up,
get yourself together.

806
00:52:29,227 --> 00:52:32,313
<i>It's a great day
for singin' a song</i>

807
00:52:32,397 --> 00:52:35,734
<i>And it's a great day
for movin' along</i>

808
00:52:35,817 --> 00:52:38,403
<i>And it's a great day
from morning to night</i>

809
00:52:38,486 --> 00:52:40,488
<i>And it's a great day</i>

810
00:52:41,906 --> 00:52:43,658
<i>For everybody's plight</i>

811
00:52:50,165 --> 00:52:52,042
How are you feeling today, Colonel?

812
00:52:52,125 --> 00:52:53,418
Super!

813
00:52:53,501 --> 00:52:55,045
Superior!

814
00:52:55,128 --> 00:52:56,755
Superfluous!

815
00:52:58,131 --> 00:53:00,467
Young Sofie here is working Thanksgiving

816
00:53:00,884 --> 00:53:03,053
because she's trying to put
herself through college.

817
00:53:03,136 --> 00:53:06,181
I told her, my young friend Charlie's
headed for college.

818
00:53:06,264 --> 00:53:07,807
Excuse me.

819
00:53:07,891 --> 00:53:09,100
Where you goin'?

820
00:53:09,184 --> 00:53:10,810
I need to use the phone.

821
00:53:10,894 --> 00:53:13,104
What's wrong with the phones in here?

822
00:53:13,646 --> 00:53:15,273
I don't want to disturb you.

823
00:53:15,357 --> 00:53:17,942
You're not disturbing me.
Make your call.

824
00:53:18,568 --> 00:53:19,694
I'd kind of like to be private.

825
00:53:19,778 --> 00:53:21,446
Stay out of my room!

826
00:53:22,655 --> 00:53:24,741
This is as private as you're gonna get.

827
00:53:27,827 --> 00:53:31,873
<i>But if you've got somethin'
that must be done</i>

828
00:53:32,665 --> 00:53:36,127
<i>And it can only be done by one</i>

829
00:53:37,962 --> 00:53:39,172
Sofia,

830
00:53:40,757 --> 00:53:43,259
what are the chances of
suitin' you up sometime?

831
00:53:44,928 --> 00:53:47,972
- Sugarbush Lodge.
- George Willis, please.

832
00:53:50,767 --> 00:53:51,893
Hello.

833
00:53:51,976 --> 00:53:53,561
George!
Hey, it's Charlie.

834
00:53:54,104 --> 00:53:57,273
Hey, Chas.
Next year you gotta come up with us.

835
00:53:57,690 --> 00:54:00,652
White powder on a base of snow bunnies.

836
00:54:02,278 --> 00:54:04,364
Chas, are you there?

837
00:54:04,989 --> 00:54:06,741
Yeah, I'm here.

838
00:54:06,825 --> 00:54:09,160
You told me to call you for the moves.

839
00:54:09,244 --> 00:54:10,495
All right.

840
00:54:10,578 --> 00:54:13,915
For now, the move's no move, status quo.

841
00:54:13,998 --> 00:54:15,708
Everything's the way we left it.

842
00:54:15,792 --> 00:54:17,252
How did we leave it?

843
00:54:18,086 --> 00:54:21,089
See no evil, hear no evil.

844
00:54:22,090 --> 00:54:24,050
You know what I mean, Chas?

845
00:54:25,677 --> 00:54:28,513
Yeah.
See no evil, hear no evil.

846
00:54:30,849 --> 00:54:32,976
Okay, then walk like you talk.

847
00:54:33,059 --> 00:54:35,311
All right, bye.

848
00:54:36,229 --> 00:54:38,022
George Willis, huh?

849
00:54:39,023 --> 00:54:40,191
Yeah.

850
00:54:40,942 --> 00:54:42,443
George Willis.

851
00:54:42,527 --> 00:54:45,780
That makes his father probably
George Willis, Senior.

852
00:54:46,865 --> 00:54:48,783
Charlie, I ask you,

853
00:54:48,867 --> 00:54:52,787
what do you think big George
is gonna feel about little George

854
00:54:52,871 --> 00:54:55,915
seeing no evil, hearing no evil?

855
00:54:58,459 --> 00:55:00,587
Well, we're not gonna tell
our parents.

856
00:55:00,795 --> 00:55:03,715
We're just gonna keep it
between ourselves.

857
00:55:04,382 --> 00:55:07,218
Oh, George isn't gonna tell his father
about this thing!

858
00:55:08,011 --> 00:55:09,179
Damn decent of him.

859
00:55:10,972 --> 00:55:13,016
- Scusi, Colonnello.
- Prego.

860
00:55:13,099 --> 00:55:14,893
I love it when you hurt me.

861
00:55:16,436 --> 00:55:18,229
Tell me now, Charlie.

862
00:55:18,313 --> 00:55:22,275
This George Willis, Jr.,
what's his father do?

863
00:55:23,234 --> 00:55:24,736
I don't really know.

864
00:55:24,819 --> 00:55:26,654
Well, I'm gonna tell you.

865
00:55:27,030 --> 00:55:28,823
When George Willis, Senior,

866
00:55:28,907 --> 00:55:31,618
isn't busy as a million-dollar man
for Aetna Casualty...

867
00:55:31,701 --> 00:55:35,496
Or is it New England distributor
for the Chrysler Corporation?

868
00:55:35,580 --> 00:55:39,584
He concerns himself with
his young son, George Willis, Jr.

869
00:55:40,543 --> 00:55:42,921
George isn't going to say anything
to his father.

870
00:55:43,004 --> 00:55:44,756
Oh, Charlie.

871
00:55:45,215 --> 00:55:47,467
Big George is gonna wind up
little George,

872
00:55:47,550 --> 00:55:50,553
and little George is gonna
sing like a canary.

873
00:55:50,637 --> 00:55:53,139
And if you're hip, kid,
you're gonna hop to too.

874
00:55:53,556 --> 00:55:55,683
You've got this all figured out,
don't you?

875
00:55:55,767 --> 00:55:59,854
It don't take no Young American merit
scholarship to figure this one out.

876
00:55:59,938 --> 00:56:01,981
Charlie, you had a little life,

877
00:56:02,065 --> 00:56:06,861
so you decided to go to the Baird school
to put yourself in the market for a big one.

878
00:56:06,945 --> 00:56:08,821
Now, in order to stay in the running,

879
00:56:08,905 --> 00:56:12,742
you're gonna have to tell these people
what they want to know.

880
00:56:13,284 --> 00:56:14,536
You think so?

881
00:56:14,619 --> 00:56:15,662
Are we finished, Sofia?

882
00:56:15,745 --> 00:56:17,413
- Yes.
- Grazie. Grazie. Andate.

883
00:56:20,875 --> 00:56:22,418
Charlie,

884
00:56:23,586 --> 00:56:25,797
if you don't sing now,

885
00:56:26,464 --> 00:56:29,842
you're gonna end up,
not only shelving biscuits

886
00:56:29,926 --> 00:56:32,887
in some convenience store
in the Oregon 'burbs,

887
00:56:32,971 --> 00:56:35,807
but probably the last word
you'll ever hear yourself say

888
00:56:35,890 --> 00:56:38,101
just before you croak,
gonna be...

889
00:56:38,184 --> 00:56:41,980
Have a nice day and come back soon.

890
00:56:42,063 --> 00:56:43,898
Sofia!

891
00:56:43,982 --> 00:56:45,733
Measure up Charlie here, pronto.

892
00:56:45,817 --> 00:56:47,777
We got a date for Thanksgiving.

893
00:56:48,444 --> 00:56:49,696
We got a date?

894
00:56:49,988 --> 00:56:51,823
My brother's place.

895
00:56:51,948 --> 00:56:55,118
W.R. Slade, White Plains, New York.

896
00:56:55,785 --> 00:56:58,162
Colonel, I can't go with you
to your brother's place.

897
00:56:58,329 --> 00:57:01,332
I mean,
I should be getting back to school.

898
00:57:04,210 --> 00:57:07,922
Well, you gotta have
Thanksgiving somewhere.

899
00:57:08,006 --> 00:57:10,091
I mean, eats and treats.

900
00:57:10,174 --> 00:57:12,010
I can use the company, Charlie.

901
00:57:15,513 --> 00:57:16,889
All right.

902
00:57:16,973 --> 00:57:18,433
Does he know I'm comin'?

903
00:57:18,516 --> 00:57:19,934
He doesn't know I'm comin'.

904
00:57:20,018 --> 00:57:23,438
But wait till you see the look on his face
when I walk through the door.

905
00:57:23,521 --> 00:57:25,064
Oh, he loves me!

906
00:57:27,358 --> 00:57:31,237
Oh, Charlie,
about your little problem,

907
00:57:31,321 --> 00:57:33,906
there are two kinds of people
in this world.

908
00:57:33,990 --> 00:57:38,202
Those who stand up and face the music,
and those who run for cover.

909
00:57:38,286 --> 00:57:39,829
Cover's better.

910
00:57:39,912 --> 00:57:42,040
Okay, Sofia, suit him up!

911
00:57:42,123 --> 00:57:43,750
Make him pretty.

912
00:58:00,224 --> 00:58:01,809
Careful.

913
00:58:03,102 --> 00:58:05,063
- Should I ring it?
- Yeah.

914
00:58:13,905 --> 00:58:16,157
- Yes?
- Yes!

915
00:58:16,324 --> 00:58:17,742
Who is this?

916
00:58:18,117 --> 00:58:19,619
It's Randy.

917
00:58:19,786 --> 00:58:21,621
Randy? You new?

918
00:58:22,705 --> 00:58:24,082
I'm your nephew.

919
00:58:24,165 --> 00:58:26,584
Here I am!

920
00:58:26,834 --> 00:58:28,669
Your sister's been hoarding me
long enough.

921
00:58:28,753 --> 00:58:31,714
Thought it's time
to spread the riches around.

922
00:58:32,131 --> 00:58:34,384
- Uncle Frank.
- Gloria!

923
00:58:34,467 --> 00:58:36,427
- Gail.
- Of course.

924
00:58:37,261 --> 00:58:40,056
Say hello to the potluck party
from New York City.

925
00:58:40,139 --> 00:58:43,518
Good old Uncle Frank and this here
with him is Charlie Simms,

926
00:58:43,601 --> 00:58:46,437
star halfback of the Baird football team.

927
00:58:46,521 --> 00:58:50,400
They not only beat Exeter and Groton,
but Aquinas High School too.

928
00:58:51,317 --> 00:58:53,069
Where's your miserable father?

929
00:58:53,152 --> 00:58:55,405
Wait! No, no.
Let's surprise him.

930
00:58:55,488 --> 00:58:59,117
Give that fat heart of his an attack.
Willie!

931
00:59:01,119 --> 00:59:02,578
Ho, Willie!

932
00:59:15,800 --> 00:59:17,301
Hello, Frank.

933
00:59:17,844 --> 00:59:20,054
- How you doin'?
- Okay.

934
00:59:20,138 --> 00:59:21,556
Here's my hand.

935
00:59:23,182 --> 00:59:25,435
Charlie, meet W.R. Slade.

936
00:59:25,601 --> 00:59:26,894
Nice to meet you, sir.

937
00:59:26,978 --> 00:59:29,731
The original bulging briefcase man.

938
00:59:29,814 --> 00:59:32,567
Gretchen, I smell those prunes!

939
00:59:32,650 --> 00:59:34,735
- We talkin' turkey Marbella?
- Yes, we are.

940
00:59:38,030 --> 00:59:39,615
Let's have a whiff.
Come on.

941
00:59:39,699 --> 00:59:41,701
You know, I always had a sneaker for you.
Come here.

942
00:59:45,955 --> 00:59:48,249
- Where are you, Garry? I heard you cough.
- Right here.

943
00:59:48,332 --> 00:59:49,959
Who are you again?

944
00:59:50,209 --> 00:59:54,922
I'm here at the Waldorf with...
Is it your brother?

945
00:59:55,006 --> 00:59:57,508
W.R.'s final issue.
How ya doin', son?

946
00:59:57,592 --> 01:00:00,094
Yeah, sure, Frank's my brother.
Who the hell are you?

947
01:00:00,845 --> 01:00:02,847
I'm takin' care of him for the weekend.

948
01:00:02,930 --> 01:00:04,098
Charlie.

949
01:00:06,142 --> 01:00:07,143
Sorry.

950
01:00:07,768 --> 01:00:09,353
Where's the booze?

951
01:00:09,770 --> 01:00:10,938
Flowin' like mud here.

952
01:00:11,022 --> 01:00:14,692
To tell the truth,
the Colonel's not well, I don't think.

953
01:00:15,151 --> 01:00:16,360
Not well?

954
01:00:16,736 --> 01:00:18,738
I think he's a little lonely.

955
01:00:19,322 --> 01:00:21,449
Why didn't you take him
to your family's for dinner?

956
01:00:21,532 --> 01:00:23,034
I heard that!

957
01:00:24,952 --> 01:00:26,370
I heard that.

958
01:00:26,454 --> 01:00:29,624
Pay no attention to him, Charlie.
That's just big-brother talk.

959
01:00:29,707 --> 01:00:32,293
He's been watching out
for me since day one.

960
01:00:32,376 --> 01:00:37,298
Bailed me out of more trouble
than he'd like to remember.

961
01:00:37,381 --> 01:00:39,258
Here, let me take your coat.

962
01:00:40,384 --> 01:00:43,513
I meant to pick up some vino
on my way up, but I blew it.

963
01:00:43,596 --> 01:00:46,140
I'll send you the Rothschild again
for Christmas,

964
01:00:46,224 --> 01:00:48,601
only let's see how Thanksgiving goes.

965
01:00:48,684 --> 01:00:50,102
I'll set two more places.

966
01:00:50,186 --> 01:00:51,562
Here's your drink, Frank.

967
01:00:51,646 --> 01:00:53,439
Oh, thank you, Randy.

968
01:00:53,523 --> 01:00:55,733
Still with Snow Queen Sugar?

969
01:00:56,317 --> 01:00:59,904
Snow Flake.
Why do you always get that wrong?

970
01:01:00,238 --> 01:01:02,281
Because it's not important
for me to get it right.

971
01:01:02,365 --> 01:01:03,991
What are you doing there now?

972
01:01:04,659 --> 01:01:06,577
I'm vice president for marketing.

973
01:01:06,744 --> 01:01:09,413
Congratulations!

974
01:01:09,622 --> 01:01:11,040
Sugar is shit though.

975
01:01:11,123 --> 01:01:14,335
I told General Abrams,
install honey in the commissaries.

976
01:01:14,418 --> 01:01:18,172
If K-50s didn't blow your brains out,
sugar, sure as shit, was gonna.

977
01:01:19,507 --> 01:01:20,508
Why don't we all sit down?

978
01:01:21,717 --> 01:01:25,513
Mitsouki. Rhymes with nookie.
Be careful.

979
01:01:25,596 --> 01:01:28,349
When the wife gets restless,
the wife gets racy.

980
01:01:28,432 --> 01:01:30,017
Well, let's go and eat, shall we?

981
01:01:30,101 --> 01:01:31,519
By all means.

982
01:01:33,104 --> 01:01:34,730
Thank you, Charlie.

983
01:01:34,814 --> 01:01:38,901
Where you wanna sit, Frank?
At the head again?

984
01:01:38,985 --> 01:01:42,780
Any old card table will do.
This is fine.

985
01:01:44,657 --> 01:01:46,033
Where was I?

986
01:01:46,117 --> 01:01:49,370
So, I wake up. It's 4:00 in the morning.
I don't know who I'm with

987
01:01:49,453 --> 01:01:51,789
or why I'm there, or where I am.

988
01:01:52,373 --> 01:01:55,251
What am I gonna do?
I got this Asian flower

989
01:01:55,710 --> 01:01:59,630
on one hand,
all giggly and dewy-like,

990
01:02:00,047 --> 01:02:04,051
and this hard-boiled Navy nurse
outta Omaha, on the other.

991
01:02:04,135 --> 01:02:07,889
We're three across the bed,
not a stitch of clothes on.

992
01:02:08,389 --> 01:02:09,765
It comes to me.

993
01:02:10,808 --> 01:02:15,146
Let east meet west.
We'll build a golden bridge.

994
01:02:17,231 --> 01:02:20,234
I felt like I'd just joined
the corps of engineers!

995
01:02:26,324 --> 01:02:27,992
We all still here?

996
01:02:28,951 --> 01:02:30,953
It's a beautiful story.

997
01:02:33,331 --> 01:02:37,084
Do you always enjoy
shocking people, Uncle Frank?

998
01:02:37,168 --> 01:02:38,252
Honey...

999
01:02:38,336 --> 01:02:40,755
I didn't know you were
so easily shocked, Randy.

1000
01:02:40,838 --> 01:02:43,049
I admire your sensibilities,
I'm touched.

1001
01:02:43,132 --> 01:02:46,093
Dad, remember the time
you persuaded Frank

1002
01:02:46,177 --> 01:02:48,262
to go to the kennel?

1003
01:02:48,346 --> 01:02:49,430
What about it?

1004
01:02:49,513 --> 01:02:51,766
He almost put the seeing eye dog business
outta business.

1005
01:02:51,849 --> 01:02:53,017
Cool it, Randy.

1006
01:02:53,100 --> 01:02:54,977
It's over and done with.

1007
01:02:55,394 --> 01:02:57,271
Indeed it is, Garry.

1008
01:02:57,355 --> 01:02:59,440
Indeed it is. So is dinner.

1009
01:02:59,523 --> 01:03:01,108
Charlie, what time you have?

1010
01:03:01,192 --> 01:03:02,693
I think we better be gettin' back.

1011
01:03:02,777 --> 01:03:05,863
You ever given any thought to
a Braille watch, Frank?

1012
01:03:05,946 --> 01:03:06,947
Randy...

1013
01:03:07,031 --> 01:03:10,576
Stevie Wonder wears one,
or do you rank on him too?

1014
01:03:10,660 --> 01:03:11,786
Honey, please.

1015
01:03:11,869 --> 01:03:14,163
It's all right, Gloria.
I enjoy Randy's observations.

1016
01:03:14,246 --> 01:03:16,374
My wife's name is Gail, Frank.

1017
01:03:16,832 --> 01:03:18,334
Can you hear that?
Gail.

1018
01:03:18,417 --> 01:03:20,711
Excuse me. Gail.

1019
01:03:21,462 --> 01:03:24,340
Gail strikes me
as a very beautiful woman,

1020
01:03:24,423 --> 01:03:27,176
but, you know,
there's a little tension in her voice.

1021
01:03:27,259 --> 01:03:30,012
I don't know what it is.
It could be one of two things,

1022
01:03:30,096 --> 01:03:32,723
either Gail is nervous
or unsatisfied.

1023
01:03:34,976 --> 01:03:36,560
What's your point, Uncle Frank?

1024
01:03:36,644 --> 01:03:38,104
You ought to go down on her.

1025
01:03:38,187 --> 01:03:40,439
